        "Two cities -- Alexandria and Antioch -- represented two approaches to reading the Bible in early Christianity. Alexandria (Clement, Origen) favored allegorical reading: every text has a deeper spiritual meaning beyond the surface. When Genesis says God 'walked in the garden,' God doesn't have legs -- the 'walking' means God's presence moving through creation. When the Song of Songs describes erotic love, it really means the love between Christ and the church. Antioch (John Chrysostom, Theodore of Mopsuestia) favored literal-historical reading: start with what the text actually says in its original context before looking for deeper meanings. The Song of Songs is a love poem. Genesis is a creation account. Respect the text's plain sense before spiritualizing it.",
      intermediate:
        "Origen developed a three-level reading system: literal (the surface meaning), moral (what it teaches about how to live), and spiritual/allegorical (the deeper mystical meaning). He believed every text had all three levels, though sometimes the literal level was deliberately absurd to force the reader to look deeper. Augustine adopted a similar approach with a crucial addition: the 'rule of charity' -- if your interpretation does not promote love of God and love of neighbor, you have misread the text.\n\nThe medieval church formalized this into the 'four senses of Scripture': literal (what happened), allegorical (what to believe), moral/tropological (how to act), and anagogical (where you are headed, i.e., heaven). The jingle: 'The letter teaches facts, the allegory what to believe, the moral what to do, the anagogy where to aim.'\n\nThe Reformation reasserted the primacy of the literal sense. Luther insisted on the 'plain sense' of Scripture against what he saw as Catholic allegorizing that could make the text say anything the church wanted. Calvin followed suit. This emphasis on literal reading eventually produced modern biblical literalism -- though neither Luther nor Calvin would recognize what American fundamentalism has done with the principle.\n\nThe irony: 'literal reading' has never meant 'taking every word at face value.' Even the most literal readers recognize poetry (Psalms), parable (Jesus' stories), and apocalyptic imagery (Revelation) as genres that require non-literal interpretation. The question is not 'literal or symbolic?' but 'what kind of text is this, and how does that genre work?'",
      advanced:
        "Henri de Lubac's monumental 'Medieval Exegesis' (4 volumes) recovered the richness of the pre-modern interpretive tradition and challenged the post-Enlightenment assumption that only historical-critical reading is 'real' scholarship. Hans Frei ('The Eclipse of Biblical Narrative') argued that the rise of historical criticism in the 18th century caused the church to lose the ability to read Scripture as a unified narrative -- reducing it to a collection of historical propositions to be verified or debunked.\n\nThe 'theological interpretation of Scripture' movement (Kevin Vanhoozer, Stephen Fowl, Ellen Davis) represents a contemporary attempt to recover pre-critical interpretive practices without abandoning critical tools. The argument: historical criticism tells you what the text meant to its original audience, but the church needs to know what the text means for the community of faith today. Both questions are legitimate, and neither alone is sufficient."
