        "For most of church history, the Bible was read by people in power: clergy, scholars, kings, and landowners. Liberation theology, emerging in Latin America in the 1960s-70s, asked: what if we read the Bible from the perspective of the poor? The answer was shocking: the Bible suddenly looked like a different book. The Exodus was not just ancient history but a paradigm for God liberating oppressed people today. Mary's Magnificat ('He has brought down the powerful from their thrones and lifted up the lowly,' Luke 1:52) was not pious poetry but a revolutionary manifesto. Jesus' first sermon ('He has sent me to proclaim freedom for the prisoners and recovery of sight for the blind, to set the oppressed free,' Luke 4:18) was not spiritual metaphor but a political program.",
      intermediate:
        "Gustavo Gutierrez ('A Theology of Liberation,' 1971) laid the foundation: God has a 'preferential option for the poor' -- not because poor people are morally superior, but because God consistently sides with the vulnerable against the powerful throughout Scripture. Jon Sobrino, Leonardo Boff, and Ignacio Ellacuria developed this in different directions. Six Jesuits at the University of Central America, including Ellacuria, were assassinated by the Salvadoran military in 1989 for their theological work -- demonstrating that liberation theology was not abstract.\n\nFeminist hermeneutics (Elisabeth Schussler Fiorenza, Phyllis Trible, Renita Weems) applied the same lens to gender: reading the Bible with attention to women's experiences reveals both the patriarchal assumptions of the text and moments of resistance and liberation within it. Postcolonial hermeneutics (R.S. Sugirtharajah, Musa Dube) reads the Bible from colonized peoples' perspectives, noting that the Bible has been used both to justify colonialism ('the conquest of Canaan') and to resist it ('Let my people go').\n\nBlack theology (James Cone, 'A Black Theology of Liberation') argued that the God of the Bible is a God who takes sides -- specifically, God sides with Black people against white supremacy. Cone's claim was not that God loves Black people more but that a God who liberates slaves in Exodus and identifies with the crucified in Jesus cannot be neutral about racial oppression. This made many white Christians uncomfortable, which Cone took as evidence that he was reading the text correctly.",
      advanced:
        "The methodological contribution of liberation hermeneutics is the 'hermeneutical circle': practice (engagement with reality) shapes interpretation, and interpretation shapes practice. You do not first study the Bible and then act. You act (work with the poor, confront injustice), then read the Bible in light of that experience, then act again informed by the text. The Bible is not a problem to be solved but a conversation partner for an ongoing struggle.\n\nCritiques of liberation hermeneutics include: it can reduce the Bible to a political manifesto, it can romanticize poverty, and it risks imposing modern political categories onto ancient texts. These critiques have force. But the counter-argument is equally strong: all reading is done from a social location, and pretending otherwise simply allows the reading of the privileged to pass as 'objective' while calling the reading of the oppressed 'biased.' The question is never 'Do you have a perspective?' but 'Whose perspective does your reading serve?'"
