      intermediate:
        "The Baptist family is enormous and internally diverse. Southern Baptists (the largest Protestant denomination in America, ~13 million members) tend toward conservative theology and politics. American Baptists tend toward moderate-progressive positions. National Baptist Convention and Progressive National Baptist Convention are historically Black denominations with deep roots in the civil rights movement (Martin Luther King Jr. was a Baptist minister). Independent Baptists range from moderate to fundamentalist.\n\nThe theological fault line within Baptist life is the tension between two founding principles: soul freedom (every person interprets Scripture for themselves) and biblical authority (the Bible is the final authority). These principles can conflict: what happens when one person's soul-free interpretation contradicts another's? Southern Baptists resolved this in the 'Conservative Resurgence' (1979-2000) by centralizing theological authority around biblical inerrancy -- which many Baptist historians argue betrayed the tradition's commitment to local autonomy and individual conscience.\n\nBaptist worship ranges from formal (some American Baptist churches use liturgy) to informal (many independent Baptist churches are spontaneous and energetic). The emphasis on personal decision ('accepting Jesus as your Lord and Savior') makes evangelism central. The altar call -- inviting people to 'come forward' to make a public commitment -- is a Baptist invention that became standard across evangelical Christianity.",
