        "Deconstruction is the trendy term for something the Christian tradition has always known: faith grows through crisis. You believe what you were taught (first naivete). You encounter something that makes that belief impossible to maintain -- suffering, hypocrisy, new information, moral failure of leaders (the crisis). You either construct a new, more mature faith on the other side (second naivete), or you leave entirely. The term 'deconstruction' comes from philosophy (Jacques Derrida) but has been adopted by ex-evangelicals and progressive Christians to describe the process of questioning inherited beliefs. Churches panic about deconstruction. But the Psalms are full of it. Job is one long deconstruction. Jesus deconstructed the Pharisees' theology in real time. The question is not whether deconstruction happens -- it is whether there is support for people going through it.",
      intermediate:
        "Paul Ricoeur's framework is the most useful: first naivete (uncritical acceptance of inherited beliefs) -> critical distance (questioning, doubt, analysis) -> second naivete (a re-chosen faith that has passed through the fire of questioning and come out deeper). The problem in many churches: they only have space for first naivete. Doubt is treated as sin. Questions are treated as rebellion. So when people inevitably reach the critical distance phase, they have no support and often leave entirely -- when what they actually needed was a community that could hold them through the transition.\n\nJames Fowler's 'Stages of Faith' maps this process developmentally: Stage 3 (Synthetic-Conventional) faith relies on the authority of the community. Stage 4 (Individuative-Reflective) faith questions that authority and constructs personal conviction. Stage 5 (Conjunctive) faith reintegrates what was lost in Stage 4 -- including mystery, paradox, and symbol. Most churches operate at Stage 3 and interpret Stage 4 as falling away rather than growing up.\n\nThe 'deconstruction' wave in American evangelicalism (2015-present) has specific triggers: the sexual abuse crisis (exposed in the Southern Baptist Convention, Catholic Church, and independent churches), white evangelical alignment with Trump (which for many younger believers contradicted Jesus' teaching), purity culture trauma (the psychological damage of abstinence-only sexual ethics), and access to information (biblical scholarship, church history, and critical thinking are now available to anyone with a phone). These are not attacks on faith. They are the removal of protective barriers that kept uncomfortable truths at bay.",
