        "The softening mechanisms are fascinating to trace. Matthew's 'poor in spirit' (5:3) spiritualizes Luke's blunt 'poor' (6:20). Clement of Alexandria (2nd century) wrote 'Who Is the Rich Man Who Shall Be Saved?' arguing that Jesus meant inner detachment from wealth, not literal poverty. The 'eye of the needle' has been explained as a small gate in Jerusalem's wall (no archaeological evidence for this -- it was invented to make the saying less radical). The prosperity gospel (Kenneth Hagin, Joel Osteen, Creflo Dollar) inverts Jesus' teaching entirely: God WANTS you to be rich, and wealth is a sign of God's blessing.\n\nThe monastic tradition took Jesus literally: vows of poverty, communal ownership, simple living. Francis of Assisi stripped naked in the public square, renounced his father's wealth, and spent his life among lepers and beggars. Dorothy Day founded the Catholic Worker movement on the premise that Christians should live among the poor and share their resources. These are minority traditions within Christianity, but they are the traditions that take Jesus' words at face value.\n\nJohn Wesley developed a practical framework: 'Earn all you can. Save all you can. Give all you can.' Wesley himself earned the equivalent of millions from his writings and gave away roughly 98% of his income, living on a fraction. The Wesleyan model acknowledges economic participation while demanding radical generosity -- a middle path between prosperity gospel and vow-of-poverty asceticism.",
